column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FORM VIGORO INDUSTRIES LOCATED IN WINTERHAVE, FL TO CLEAN HARBORS TECHNOLOGY CORP., INC. LOCATED 5 MILES SOUTH OF KIMBALL ON HIGHWAY 71 IN KIMBALL, NE. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA.  UPON ARRIVAL AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC., THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION WAS BEING TRANSFERRED TO A SECOND TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHEN IT SLIPPED FROM THE FORK TRUCK ONTO ITS SIDE AND BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE TOP BUNG CAP ONTO THE CONCRETE DOCK AREA WHERE THE IN-TRANSIT TRANSFER WAS BEING CONDUCTED.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH SPEEDI DRY AND REPOSITIONED THE CONTAINER IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION.  ADDITIONAL SPEEDI DRY WAS USED TO ABSORB ALL FREE LIQUIDS RELEASED FROM THE CONTAINER.  THE SPILL DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. FACILITY PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE CONTAINER IN QUESTIONS AND DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER PORTION OF THE BUNG CAP WAS MISSING ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPED WHEN IT TIPPED OVER.  A REPLACEMENT BUNG CAP WAS USED TO SECURE THIS CONTAINER FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY IDENTIFIED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO LEAVING THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL DRUMS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED BY THE DRIVER.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL CLOSURE DEVICES ARE PRESENT AND ARE IN PROPER WORKING ORDER PRIOR TO INITIATING THE SHIPMENT.

OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING A RAIL CAR TO A TANK TRILER.  HE CONNECTED A 2" LIQUID HOSE LINE TO HIS TRAILER, WHICH IS AN ACME FITTING, AND WENT UP TO THE TOP OF THE RAIL CAR AND HOOKED UP HIS VAPOR AND LIQUID LINE CONNECTIONS.  WHEN HE CRACKED THE LIQUID VALVE ON THE RAIL CAR HE HEARD A HISSING SOUND AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVE.  HE DISCOVERED A LEAK AT THE HOSE CONNECTION TO HIS TRAILER.  HE ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE ACME FITTING AND THIS CAUSED AMMONIA TO ESCAPE.  CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS DETERMINED TO BE THAT THE CONECTION FROM THE ACME FITTING AT THE END OF THE 2" HOSE TO THE TANK TRAILER VALVE WAS IMPROPERLY MADE BY THE DRIVER/OPERTOR.

column168: A RUST CHEMICAL CIRCULATOR TRUCK DEPARTED A CUSTOMERS SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 1610.  THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING ONE 300 GALLON STAINLESS STEEL "TOTE" SECURED BY ONE TWO-INCH RATCHET STRAP.  THE TOTE WAS STORED IN A THREE SIDED CARGO STORAGE AREA BETWEEN THE FORWARD CIRCULATOR TANK AND THE CAB OF THE TRUCK.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1615, AND ONE MILE INTO THE TRUCK BACK TO THE LAPORTE OFFICE, THE TRUCK MADE A RIGHT TURN OFF BAY AREA ONTO PORT ROAD.  THE TWO-INCH STRAP BROKE DURING THE TURN, AND THE TOTE SLID OFF THE DRIVER'S SIDE AND ONTO THE ROAD WHERE THE TOP POPPED OFF AND APPROXIMATELY 190 GALLONS SPILLED (AFTER CLEANING UP APPROXIMATELY 160 GALLONS RELEASED).  LA PORTE SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY USING A NEARBY  PHONE.  ANOTHER RUST EMPLOYEE FOLLOWING THE SAME ROUTE IN HIS PERSONAL VEHICLE ARRIVED WITHIN A COUPLE OF MINUTES AND STOPPED TO RENDER AID AND HELP DIRECT TRAFFIC AT THE SCENE.  LA PORTE SAFETY ARRIVED WITHIN 15 MINUTES AND BEGAN COORDINATING SPILL RESPONSE ACTION.  SPILL CLEAN-UP CONSISTED OF RECOVERING AS MUCH FREE LIQUID AS POSSIBLE WITH A VACUUM TRUCK THEN APPLYING ABOUT 750 POUNDS OF CITRIC ACID FROM BAGS AND BROOMING ONTO CONTAMINATED ROADWAY TO NEUTRALIZE THE REMAINING CAUSTIC (THE ROADS FROM THE INTERSECTION).  AFTER SOLUTION WAS NEUTRALIZED, DIRT AND SAND WAS USED TO ABSORB IT SO IT COULD BE SWEPT UP AND DRUMMED.  FINALLY A COUNTY SAND TRUCK WAS ROLLED INTO SAND ROADWAYS (PORT ROAD) TO PREVENT SKIDDING. APPROXIMATELY TWO YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRASS WAS REMOVED FROM THE ROAD SIDE AND RETURNED TO RUST LA PORTE YARD FOR ADDITIONAL TREATMENT/NEUTRALIZATION BEFORE RETURNING IT TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  BAY AREA BOULEVARD WAS CLOSED APPROXIMATELY TWO HOURS AND PORT ROAD FIVE HOURS. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP ENTIRELY BY RUST EXCEPT FOR FINAL SANDING, AND CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES WERE APPROVED ON SITE BY HARRIS COUNTY POLLUTION CONTROL INVESTIGATOR.  INSTITUTED A COMPREHENSIVE LOAD SECUREMENT PROGRAM TO INCLUDE SECUREMENT STRAP INVENTORY, INSPECTION, AND TRACKING. DEVELOPED STRAP INSPECTION GUIDELINES/FAILURE CRITERIA.  RETRAINING ALL OPERATORS AND SUPERVISORS ON LOAD SECUREMENT REQUIREMENTS AND TECHNIQUES. INVENTORY, NUMBER AND INSPECT ALL STRAPS CURRENTLY IN USE.  REMOVE FROM SERVICE AND DISCARD ANY NOT MEETING SPECIFICATIONS.  EVALUATE ALL TRUCKS AND TRAILERS FOR NEED OF PERMANENTLY MOUNTED STRAPS (4 INCH) PRIORITIZE AND DEVELOP COST ANALYSIS FOR REFITTING.  DEVELOP/ IMPLEMENT MOBILE SPILL RESPONSE TRAILER APPLICABLE TO ALL VARIETIES OF ROADWAY SPILLS WHICH MAY OCCUR. DEVELOP OFF-SITE SPILL RESPONSE PROCEDURES TO INCLUDE NOTIFICATIONS, COMMUNICATIONS, CONTRACT HELP AND WORKER SAFETY.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT RECEIVER, DRIVER FOUND THAT ONE DRUM INSIDE THE TRAILER HAD LEAKED IN TRANSIT.  THE DRUM WAS REMOVED AND ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED FROM THE FLOOR.  ALL WASTE WAS ACCEPTED BY THE RECEIVER FOR DISPOSAL.

AT 4:45P. ON WEDNESDAY APRIL 10, 1996 THE N & M TRANSFER SAFETY DEPARTMENT RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM AN N & M DRIVER REGARDING A SPILL IN HIS TRAILER.  THE DRIVER ADVISED THAT HE HAD JUST PULLED IN TO A DOCK AT MOLDED DIMENSIONS, PORT WASHINGTON, WI, WHEN HE NOTICED LIQUID POURING OUT THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER.  THE DRIVER WAS AWARE THAT THE ONLY LIQUID CONTAINER WITHIN THE BACK HALF OF HIS TRAILER WAS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (FLAMMABLE LIQUID) JUST PICKED UP AT THE PREVIOUS STOP.  SAFETY IMMEDIATELY ASKED HIM IF THE MATERIAL WAS POURING IN TO ANY KIND OF A DRAIN OR SEWER WITHIN THE DOCK.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CHECKED AND ADVISED THAT IT WAS POURING IN TO A DRAIN NEXT TO THE BUILDING WITHIN THE DOCK AREA.  THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO HALT THE FLOW OF THE MATERIAL ANY FURTHER.  EMPLOYEES AT MOLDED DIMENSIONS CALLED THE LOCAL PORT WASHINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT.  FIRE, POLICE, AND EMERGENCY GOVERNMENT PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE CALL.  THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS 8 BIG RACKS ON WHEELS THAT THE DRIVER FAILED TO SECURE PROPERLY.  (THE DRIVER STATES THAT HE DID SECURE THE RACKS WITH A LOAD LOCK, BUT THE FORCE OF THE RACKS BROKE THE LOAD LOCK IN TWO).  WHEN THE RACKS BROKE LOOSE, THEY RAMMED THE METAL (55) GALLONS DRUM.  ALL 55 GALLONS WERE LOST AT THE SCENE.  A PRIVATE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CALLED IN FROM FOND DU LACE, WI.  THIS COMPANY DID COMPLETE DECONTAMINATION OF THE GROUNDS, TRAILER, AND DRAINAGE SYSTEM LOCATED ON MOLDED DIMENSIONS PROPERTY.  AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT, N & M TRANSFER WAS STILL INVESTIGATING THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT. DISCIPLINARY ACTION WILL BE DELEGATED TO THE DRIVER IF SUBSTANTIAL EVIDENCE OF IMPROPER BLOCKING IS FOUND.

THIS CAUSED THE TRUCKS OFF LOADING PUMP TO CREATE A PRESSURE SURGE, THERE BY BLOWING A CLOSING CAP OFF OF AN IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE TRUCK AND PUMP BUT WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE 20 GALLON RELEASE OF FUEL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER HAD BEEN OFF DUTY SINCE 4/2/96 @ 3:00PM, HE CALLED IN ON 4/3/96 AND WAS GIVEN DISPATCH FOR A 5:00PM FOREMAN ARKANSAS DELIVERY ON 4/6/WHICH ALREADY PRELOADED FOR HIM.  FROM THIS POINT ON WE HEARD NOTHING FROM THE DRIVER UNTIL THE ACCIDENT.  UPON SPEAKING WITH THE DRIVER (WHO RECEIVED A MINOR CONCUSSION) HE REMEMBERS ONLY TALKING TO ANOTHER TRUCK DRIVER ON HIS C.B. RADIO FROM THE TIME HE DID HIS TIRE CHECK IN ROYCE CITY @ MILE MARKER 79, (ACCIDNET WAS @ THE 151 MILE MARKER) UNTIL WAKING UP IN THE AMBULANCE. THE D.P.S. OFFICER INVESIGATING THE ACCIDENT STATES HE DROVE OFF THE ROADWAY ONTO THE SOUTH SHOULDER TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 400 FEET AND ROLLED OVER APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 TIMES COMING TO REST ON IT'S LEFT SIDE. THE INVESITGATION ALSO STATED IN HIS REPORT THAT HE DID NOT OBSERVE ANY EVIDENCE INDICATING THAT THE DRIVER MADE ANY JERKING EVASIVE ACTIONS. UPON NOTIFICATION WE WERE INFORMED THAT A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON A DOME WAS LOOSENED DURING THE ROLLOVER.  EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE DISPATCHED & ON THE SCENE WITH 5 HOURS.  MIKE CLOONEN (VICE PRESIDENT *& EMREGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR) * MYSELF WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN 3 1/2 HOURS FROM NOTIFICATION.  UPON ARRIVING @ THE SCENE WE LEARNED THE LEAK WAS ONLY A MINOR DRIP AND HAD BEEN STOPPED.  AFTER GIVING THE EMREGENCY PERSONNEL THE INFORMATION THEY NEEDED, I LEFT AND WENT TO THE HOSPITAL TO SPEAK WITH OUR TEXAS OFFICE.  THE TRUCK & TRAILER HAVE BEEN COMPLETELY GONE OVER AND NO DEFECTS WERE FOUND.  THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED 4-10-96. WE HOLD REGULAR SAFETY MEETINGS AND DISCUSS PROBLEMS SUCH AS THIS. BESIDES TERMINATION OF ANY DRIVER THAT HAS AN UNEXCUSABLE ACCIDENT, WE ALSO BROUGHT THE TOTALED OUT TRUCK TO OUR SHOP FOR ALL OF THE OTHER DRIVER AND FAMILIES TO SEE.  SINCE WE CAN FIND NO REASON WHAT SO EVER FOR THIS ACCIDENT, I AM HOPEFUL THAT SEEING THE ACTUAL TRUCK ITSELF MIGHT HAVE A POSITIVE EFFECT.

THE CEMENT HOPPERS COUPLED INTO AN EMPTY BULKHEAD FLATCAR (TTLX855220) WHICH TELESCOPED INTO A LOADED TANK CAR OF HCI (GATX45951) WHICH WAS STANDING IN TRACK C12.  THE COUPLER OF TTLX 855220 PUNCTURED THE B END OF GATX 45951 ALLOWING LIQUID PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED. APPROXIMATELY 15,000 GALLONS OF 30% HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS RELEASED. RESPONSE TO THIS INCIDENT INCLUDED THE BALTIMORE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT, VISTA CHEMICAL, AND A&A ENVIRONMENTAL, A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT USED WATER TO DECONTAMINATE EQUIPMENT WHICH WAS STANDING NEAR THE AFFECTED CAR. AGRICULTURAL LIME AND CAUSTIC SODA WERE APPLIED TO THE AREAS WHERE ACID WAS SPILLED.  THE RESIDUAL CONTENTS OF GATX 45951 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A TANK TRUCK AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO VISTA CHEMICAL FOR REPACKAGING.  THE ACID WHICH HAD POOLED ON THE GROUND, APPROXIMATELY 3,000 GALLONS, WAS VACUMMED INTO A TRUCK AND ALSO TAKEN TO VISTA CHEMICAL.  AFTER APPLICATION OF NEUTRALIZING AGENTS THE AREA WAS TESTED AND FOUND TO BE SUITABLE TO RESUME OPERATIONS BY THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT.
TANK CAR LOAD SULFURIC ACID, SPENT, NOTED SPLASH LEAK DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  TANK CAR ISOLATED.  SHIPPER RESPONSE TEAM REPLACED DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET.  TANK CAR RELEASED.

column168: THE TANK TRAILER HAD BEEN UNLOADING INTO A STORAGE TANK AT THE CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING AREA FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES WHEN A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED ON A FLANGE GASKET ON THE CONNECTION OF THE OUTLET PIPE TO THE MAIN BARREL OF THE TANK TRAILER.  THE COMPRESSED AIR GOING INTO THE TANK TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF AND THE PRESSURE ON THE TRAILER WAS RELIEVED.  ENSIGN BICKFORD EMERGENCY CREWS WERE CALLED IN AND THATCHER COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREWS WERE NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED.  THE AREA WAS DIKED WITH SODA ASH AND WATER WAS SPRAYED ON THE LEAK AREA.  A SUCTION PUMP WAS USED TO OFF-LOAD THE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT ON THE TANK TRAILER.  OFF LOADING WAS COMPLETED BEFORE THATCHER COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL ARRIVED. APPROXIMATELY 80 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE RECOVERED AND APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS WERE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.  NO PRODUCT ESCAPED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE GASKET THAT FAILED WAS A LAYER TEFLON GASKET.  THERE WAS A CUT IN ONE OF THE NON-TEFLON LAYERS.  WE ARE NOW USING A NEW TYPE OF FLANGE GASKET.  IN ADDITION, WE HAVE DESIGNED A SPILL COLLAR THAT CAN BE PLACED OVER A LEAKING FLANGE IN CASE OF AN EMERGENCY SO THAT THE LEAK COULD BE CONTROLLED AND THE TANK TRAILER OFF LOADED.

AT APPROXIMATELY, 0800 HOURS, THURSDAY, APRIL 18, 1996, A CONRAIL TRAIN CREW REPORTED PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM TOP OF RAIL TANK CAR RCRX 1276 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID, SOLUTION) CAR LOCATED CONRAIL CONWAY, PA. RAIL YARD. THE RAIL CAR WAS ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  THE RAIL CAR WAS INSPECTED BY CONRAIL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD MANAGER AND A.A.R.B.O.E. INSPECTOR L. KERTING. REPAIRS ACCOMPLISHED AT 1100 HOURS, APRIL 18, 1996, RAIL CAR SECURED.  RAIL CAR RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION TO BE FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

SPILL KIT FROM TRUCK WAS USED TO STEM FLOW ON ASPHALT AND GRAVEL DIRT MATRIX.  FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND BEGAN CONTAINMENT MEASURES, WHICH CONSISTED OF COVERING SPILL WITH SAND. APPROXIMATELY 20 TONS OF SAND USED TO COVER AND CONTAIN AFFECTED AREA. KENTUCKY STATE ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICERS PRESENT DURING CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP.  CLEANUP CONTRACTOR USED WAS SUBTECU FROM EVANSVILLE, IND.  THREE ROLLOFF BOXES WERE USED TO STORE ONSITE ALL CONTAMINATED SAND, GRAVEL AND DIRT.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE, FLOAT TYPE, MAY HAVE MALFUNCTIONED AND CAUSED IMPEDENCE IN DELIVERY RESULTING IN SPILL.  OPD WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED AS PREVENTATIVE MEASURE.

column168: TRANSPORT VEHICLE NORTHBOUND ON HWY 431.  PASSENGER VEHICLE STOPPED TO MAKE LEFT TURN ONTO CROSS STREET, BRICK SCHOOL ROAD.  IN ORDER TO AVOID COLLISION, DRIVER TRIED TO RIDE SHOULDER BUT SHOULDER WAS TOO NARROW. TRANSPORT VEHICLE WENT DOWN FIVE FOOT EMBANKMENT AND ROLLED OVER 180 DEGREES.  RESIDENTS IN AREA NOTIFIED EMERGENCY SERVICES AND HELPED DRIVER FROM VEHICLE.  DRIVER NOTIFIED TERMINAL MANAGER WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED WRECKER SERVICE AND FERGUSON HARBOR CLEANUP CONTRACTOR.  ALL POSSIBLE PRODUCT PUMPED OUT OF CARGO TANK INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.  TRANSPORT VEHICLE UPRIGHTED AND TOWED TO SERVICE FACILITY IN NASHVILLE, TN. ABSORBENTS USED TO SOP UP SPILLED MATERIAL WHILE TRANSPORT VEHICLE EMPTIED AND UPRIGHTED.  CONTAMINATED DIRT DUG UP AND STORED ON AND UNDER PLASTIC COVERING ON SITE UNTIL DISPOSAL FACILITY COULD BE ARRANGED.

column58: Hose; Loading or Unloading Lines; Vent
column168: A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO 151 RAYMOND BOULEVARD IN NEWARK, NJ IN ORDER TO LOAD AND TRANSPORT A SHIPMENT OF NON-REGULATED RAINWATER FOR DISPOSAL.  PRIOR TO DISPATCH, THE DRIVER PERFORMED THE REQUIRED PRE-TRIP INSPECTION ON THE VEHICLE HE WAS ASSIGNED TO OPERATE.  THIS INCLUDED AN INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE'S SCRUBBER SYSTEM WHICH IS CONDUCTED IN ORDER TO INSURE THAT THERE IS NO RESIDUAL MATERIAL IN THIS UNIT FROM A PREVIOUS SHIPMENT.  THE DRIVER FOUND NO RESIDUAL MATERIAL IN THIS SYSTEM DURING THIS INSPECTION.  ********  UPON ARRIVAL AT 151 RAYMOND BOULEVARD, THE DRIVER INITIATED THE LOADING PROCEDURES.  AS HE STARTED THE VACUUM SYSTEM, APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE EXHAUST STACK OF THE SCRUBBER SYSTEM ONTO A FULLY CONTAINED LOADING AREA WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM CONTAMINATING THE SOIL AT THE SITE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE LOADING OPERATION AND CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED A COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE.  AT THIS POINT, THE COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE WHO ARRIVED AT THE RELEASE LOCATION, NOTIFIED THE SITE CONTACT.  A CLEAN-UP CREW WAS ALSO DISPATCHED IN ORDER TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL DEBRIS.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE CREW ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND PLACED THESE, ALONG WITH ALL OTHER SPILL DEBRIS INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM.  THIS CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING OFF-SITE DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  IN ADDITION, THE SPILL AREA WAS PRESSURE WASHED TO REMOVE RESIDUAL STAINING CAUSED BY THE MATERIAL RELEASED FROM THE EXHAUST STACK.  APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF RINSE WATER WAS COLLECTED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL ALONG WITH THE RAINWATER ORIGINALLY SLATED FOR DISPOSAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD.  PLEASE NOTE THAT PURSUANT TO THE REQUIREMENTS OF CLEAN HARBOR'S NEW JERSEY HAZARDOUS AND SOLID WASTE TRANSPORTER PERMITS, THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION ("NJDEP") AND WAS ASSIGNED CASE # 96-4-10-1044-46.  IN ADDITION, PLEASE NOTE THAT THE PROPERTY OWNER OF THE SITE WHERE CLEAN HARBORS EXPERIENCED THE RELEASE WAS NOT INVOLVED IN THIS RELEASE AND WAS NOT REQUIRED TO NOTIFY FEDERAL OR STATE AGENCIES. ********* A REVIEW OF THE VEHICLE INDICATED THAT MATERIAL FROM A PREVIOUS SHIPMENT HAD EITHER SOLIDIFIED OR FROZE IN THE EXHAUST LINE OF THE SCRUBBER SYSTEM.  THIS PREVENTED THE RESIDUAL MATERIAL FROM COLLECTING IN THE PORTION OF THE SCRUBBER SYSTEM WHICH IS ROUTINELY CHECKED PRIOR TO INITIATING ANY LOADING OPERATIONS.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE FORCE OF STARTING THE VACUUM SYSTEM FORCED THE BLOCKAGE THROUGH THE EXHAUST STACK ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO BE RELEASED. ******* IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE DRIVER OF THIS VEHICLE HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL ANCILLARY EQUIPMENT IS INSPECTED PRIOR TO INITIATING ANY LOADING AND/OR UNLOADING PROCEDURES TO INSURE THAT THIS SYSTEM IS FREE OF ANY RESIDUAL MATERIAL.

column168: CARRIER VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING WEST BOUND ON US HWY 40 APPROXIMATELY 20 MILES WEST OF KREMMLING, COLORADO.  AS A CARRIER VEHICLE TOPPED AN INCLINE, HE MET TWO EAST BOUND VEHICLE ONE PASZSING THE OTHER.  ONE OF THE EAST BOUND VEHICLES WAS IN THE WEST BOUND LANE MAKING THE PASS, CARRIER VEHICLE MOVED TO THE RIGHT IN AN ATTEMPT TO AVOID A HEAD ON COLLISION.  AS HE MOVED TO THE RIGHT, CARRIER VEHICLE DROPPED RIGHT FRONT WHEEL OFF PAVEMENT INTO MUD ON SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY.  THE MUD AND SOFT SHOULDER PULLED LOADED VEHICLE COMPLETELY OFF PAVEMENT INTO BARROW PIT WHERE UPSET AND CAME TO REST ON ITS RIGHT SIDE.  WHEN THE CARGO TANK HIT THE GROUND THE INNER PRESSURE CAUSED THE FRONT COMPARTMENT DOME LID TO POP OPEN TO SAFETY LATCH AND BEGAN TO LEAK.  WHEN VEHICLE STOPPED MOVING DRIVER IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO TRY TO GET OUT OF THE VEHICLE.  AFTER DRIVER GOT OUT AND WALKED AROUND THE VEHICLE HE NOTICED THE DOME LID OPENED AND LEAKING, DRIVER THEN PUSHED DOME LID CLOSED AND LATCHED IT.  THE DOME LID RESEALED AND STOPPED LEAKING.
FEEDER WAS EMPTY.  PUT ON GLOVES, APRON & GOGGLES.  CLEARED AWAY LEAKING BOX AFTER ASESSING SITUATION AND BY USING THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET AND THE DECISION TREE.

column168: THE DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER WHICH THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED ON AND WAS PREPARING TO TRANSFER IT TO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR DELIVERY WHEN HE SMELLED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE UNLOADED THREE DRUMS AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING FOURTH DRUM WHICH HAD BEEN PLACED ON A PALLET WITH THE FORKLIFT WHEN IT FELL OVER.  HE STATED HE WAS MOVING A LITTLE FASTER THAN NORMAL DUE TO THE FACT HE WAS AFRAID THERE MAY BE A LEAK. WHEN THE DRUM FELL, THE LID POPPED OFF WHICH CAUSED THE CONTENTS TO LEAK ALL OVER THE DOCK.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS IMMEDIATELY SINCE THE SHIPPER & CONSIGNEE WERE THE SAME AND THEY WERE INSTRUCTED TO USE SAWDUST OR OTHER ABSORBENT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. SEQUENCE OF EVENTS:  THE CONTENTS IN THE SUPERSACK GOT BETWEEN THE PLASTIC LINER AND THE SUPERSACK ITSELF.  THE MATERIAL HAD FREE FLOWING CORROSIVE LIQUID IN THE MIXTURE OF SOLID MATERIAL.  BEING OF A CORROSIVE NATURE IT BEGAN TO EAT THE SUPERSACK, WHEN IT GOT BETWEEN THE INNER LINER AND THE SUPERSACK.  THAT PLUS THE FACT THAT THE SUPERSACK WAS FILLED BEYOND SPECIFICATION CAUSED THE SUPERSACK TO SPLIT OPEN AT ITS SIDE WALL LESS THAN 24 MILES AFTER PICKING UP THE MATERIAL.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THE BAG SHIFTING AND PULLED OVER TO INSPECT THE SUPERSACK.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER HE SAW THAT THE SUPERSACK HAD SPLIT DOWN THE SIDE.  THE DRIVER USED PLASTIC MATERIAL FROM THE ON BOARD EMERGENCY RESPONSE KIT TO PROTECT THE GROUND AND TO CATCH ANY DRIPPINGS.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED HIS HOMEBASE TO REQUEST OVER PACKS AND MAN POWER TO SHOVEL THE CONTENTS INTO THE OVER PACK DRUMS. ********* DESCRIPTION OF RESPONSE:  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE REMAINED WITH HIS VEHICLE UNTIL HELP ARRIVED FROM HIS HOMEBASE. AT THAT TIME PLASTIC WAS PUT ON THE FLOOR OF THE FLATBED AND THE MATERIAL WAS SHOVELED OUT OF THE SUPERSACK AND INTO THE OVERPACK DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WERE LABELED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE MANIFEST WAS CHANGED TO REFLECT THE CONTAINER CHANGE, AND THE MATERIAL WAS SENT TO THE HOMEBASE TO BE HELD FOR 10 DAYS PENDING COORDINATON TO THE TSDF FOR FINAL DISPOSAL.  ******** ACTION TAKEN:  THE GENERATOR OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS INFORMED BY PHONE THAT THE SUPERSACK WAS OVER FILLED AND THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE SUPERSACK WERE NOT SOLID AS DESCRIBED ON THE MANIFEST, AND THAT THE MATERIAL HAD GOTTEN ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE INNER PLASTIC LINER.  ****** RECOMMENDATIONS: 1) PUT THE PRODUCT INTO STEEL DRUMS.  2) WEIGH EACH CONTAINER TO ENSURE THAT IT IS NOT FILLED BEYOND D.O.T. SPECIFICATIONS FOR THAT CONTAINER.  3) ENSURE THAT THE MATERIAL IS SOLID.

DRIVER HAD BEEN PUMPING OFF PRODUCT FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR WITH PUMP ON TRACTOR.  THE MALE END WHICH WAS HOOKED UP TO CONSIGNEE'S OUTLET CAME APART.  THE HOSE END SLIPPED OFF THE SHANK OF THE FITTING.  HOSE WAS REPAIRED AND TESTED.  HOSE END WAS CUT OFF AND IS BEING EXAMINED BY MECHANICS TO DETERMINE WHY IT FAILED.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN PIT AND CLEANED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE.

CONTACTED SHIPPER WHO IS EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER.  SHIPPER REPLACED RUPTURED DISK.

UTLX 89101 BROUGHT INTO CAR SHOP AT YARD ON THIRD SHIFT.  THEY STATED THAT THEY COULD SMELL THE PRODUCT.  CAR WAS MOVED BACK OUTSIDE.  AT 0916, 4/29/96, THE FOREMAN CHARLIE MINDERHOUT STATED THAT HE COULD NOT SMELL ANYTHING AROUND THE CAR AND THERE WAS NO APPARENT LEAK.  CONTACTED SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC, SHIPPER SENT A RESCAR REPS WHO DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE O-RING WAS MISSING.  THEY REPLACED THE O-RING ON 4/30/96.

column168: TANK CAR UTLX 644777 WAS PLACED ON STEAM FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 TO 3 HOURS ON APRIL 2ND AT THE FLEXI-FLO SITE IN SCULLY YARD.  AT THAT TIME THE CAR IMPLODED FOR AN AREA 15 FEET IN LENGTH AT THE MANWAY.  AMOCO AND UTLX INSPECTED THE CAR ON APRIL 4TH.  AMOCO DIRECTED FLEXI-FLO TO RE-HEAT THE CAR ON APRIL 8TH; HEATING COMMENCED AT 1000 HOURS ON APRIL 9TH AND CONTINUED FOR 3 HOURS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1330 HOURS, MATERIAL SHOT OUT OF THE OPEN FILL HOLE.  CONRAIL FLEXI-FLO EMPLOYEES CLEANED UP THE SPILT PRODUCT.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: DURING CHECK OF LOAD, DRIVER DISCOVERED ONE OF THE FIBER BOXES IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE.  THE SPLIT WAS PATCHED WITH SILICONE AND ALL SPILLAGE ABSORBED.  ALL CARGO AND SPILL RESIDUE WAS ACCEPTED AT THE RECEIVING FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.

OUR UNIT WAS AT THE HALTERMAN CHEMICAL PLANT IN HOUSTON, TEXAS TO UNLOAD. THE PLANT OPERATOR PUT NITROGEN PRESSURE ON OUR TRAILER AND OPENED UP THE INTERNAL VALVE AND THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO DRIP FROM THE BOTTOM SEAM.  THE PLANT SUPERVISOR RONNIE LIMA STATED, "THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP AND BEING THAT IT WAS A HOLIDAY AND THEY WERE UNABLE TO CONTACT ANYONE, THEY WOULD WAIT UNTIL MONDAY (04-08-96) TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER.  ON O4-08-96 RON INLOW WENT WITH A DIP TUBE AND UNLOADED THE PRODUCT WITH NO PROBLEMS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TRUCK WAS PUMPING PRODUCT FROM OUR CARGO TANK INTO CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK. DURING THE COURSE OF PUMPING, THE CAMLOCK EARS CONNECTING THE HOSE TO OUR CARGO TANK VIBRATED OPEN ALLOWING THE HOSE TO BECOME DISCONNECTED.  BY THE TIME WE GOT THE PUMP SHUT DOWN, WE LOST APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL FUEL COVERING AN AREA OF 15' X 20'.  OUR DRIVERS CLEANED UP THE SPILL USING MATERIALS DESIGNED TO SOAK UP PETROLEUM PRODUCTS.  WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO ASSIST WITH THE CLEANUP, REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND REPLACEMENT WITH CLEAN.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AT THE COUNTY LANDFILL.  ALL OF OUR TRUCKS ARE EQUIPPED WITH SECURING STRAPS TO PREVENT THESE EARS FROM VIBRATING OPEN. WE WILL EMPHASIZE IN FUTURE TRAINING THE PROPER USE OF THESE SECURING DEVICES.  NO FURTHER ACTION IS ANTICIPATED AT THIS TIME.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ON TR# 9378 FOR DELIVERY ON THRUSDAY 4/11/96 AND THE DRIVER LEFT FOR HIS DELIVERIES.  HE WAS IN THE PINE CASTLE AREA OF ORLANDO AND GOT LOST. HE PROCEEDED ACROSS THE TRACKS AND THEN HEARD THE TRAIN SOUND ITS WHISTLE.  HE TURBED TO HIS LEFT AND SAW IT BEARING DOWN ON HIM, SO HE GAVE THE TRUCK FULL GAS (PEDAL) AND PROCEEDED ACROSS. THE TRAIN WAS ESTIMATED TO BE DOING AROUND 79 MILES PER HOUR BY FLA HWY PATROL OFFICER.  DRIVER COULD NOT GET ACROSS IN TIME.  THE TRAIN STRUCK THE TRAILER JUST IN FRONT OF THE BACK WHEELS AND SPLIT THE TRAILER IN HALF. THIS SHIPMENT OF 20 CNS OF PAINT WAS IN THE AREA WHERE THE RAIL STRUCK DESTROYED ALL OF IT.  WE CALLED SHIPPER AND ALSO CHEMICAL CONSERVATION CORP IN ORLANDO AND HAD THEM GO TO THE SIGHT OF THE ACCIDENT TO CLEAN THIS UP.

column168: AT APPROX. 10:30 ON 4-17-96, THE TERMINAL WAS NOTIFIED BY OUR SALES REP. THAT ONE OF HER ACCOUNTS HAD CONTACTED HER AND SAID ONE OF THEIR EMPLOYEE'S REQUIRED MEDICAL ATTENTION DUE TO A HAZMAT SPILL.  WE ALSO HAD ANOTHER CALL FROM A CONSIGNEE THAT STATED THEIR EMPLOYEE HAD TOUCHED THE S/W ON A PALLET AND HIS HANDS WERE BURNING.  WE IDENTIFIED THE ABOVE SHIPMENT AS THE MATERIAL WHICH HAD LEAKED.  WE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER AND OBTAINED HEALTH INFORMATION ON THE PRODUCT.  THIS INFORMATION WAS RELAYED TO THE CUSTOMERS.  AFTER RESEARCHING THIS INCIDENT, IT WAS FOUND THE PRODUCT IS SHIPPED WITH A VENT PLUG TO CONTROL EXPANSION AND A HOLE IS POKED IN THE CAP COVERING THE VENT PLUG.  AS A RESULT A STRONG ODOR IS CONSTANTLY ESCAPING FROM THE DRUM.  ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER, THE TWO DRUMS WERE LOADED ON A SKID AND SHRINK WRAPPED TOGETHER.  WHILE IN TRANSIT, ONE OF THE HORIZONTAL BOARDS ON THE SKID BROKE RESULTING IN ONE OF THE DRUMS BREAKING THROUGH THE SKID WHICH CAUSED IT TO LEAN AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE.  IT DID NOT COMPLETELY TIP OVER, BUT THE ANGLE WAS PROBABLY ENOUGH TO ALLOW SOME OF THE PRODUCT TO LEAK ON TO THE OTHER FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER.  ABF PICKED UP THE DAMAGED SHIPMENTS AND THEY WILL EITHER BE RE-WORKED OR DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE REGULATIONS. WE WILL NOT ACCEPT ANY MORE FREIGHT FROM THIS CUSTOMER UNTIL THEY IMPROVE THEIR PACKAGING.

column168: THE INCIDENT WAS HAPPENED AROUND 14:40, APRIL 29, 1996.  SUBJECT SHIPMENT WAS ON THE WAY TO THE THIRD COUNTRY VIA JAPAN.  IN ACCORDANCE WITH ORDINARY ROUTE AND PROCEDURES IT WAS BROUGHT TO IACT WAREHOUSE ONCE AS ONE OF TRANSFER SHIPMENTS AFTER UNLOADING FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  AT THAT BONDED WAREHOUSE, WHILE THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING CHECKED IT WAS TILTED ERRONEOUSLY, A HOLE WAS PUNCHED ON THE DRUM CAN AND THE 1/4 OF THE CONTENT DRAINED OUT. IN ACCORDANCE WITH EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDANCE FOR DANGEROUS GOODS INCIDENT, WE COPED WITH THE SITUATION CAREFULLY.  AFTER RECEIVING THE INCIDENT REPORT, THE MANAGER ON DUTY CONFIRMED PROPER SHIPPING NAME IN SHIPPERS D\G DECLARATION AND REFERRED TO EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK FOR THE SHIPMENTS' POTENTIAL HAZARDS AND EMERGENCY ACTION.  AT THE SAME TIME, THE MANAGER ON DUTY EYE-WITNESSED THE SPOT.  IN CONSIDERATION OF CHARACTERISTICS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID, THE LIQUID LICKED OUT WAS ABSORBED BY SAND.  FOR THE REMAINING LIQUID IN THE DRUM, GUM TAPING WAS APPLIED WITH THE COVERAGE OF SHRINK WRAP OVER THE HOLE.  THE SPOT WAS CIRCLED WITH ROPES IN ITS DIAMETER OF 8 METERS AND ISOLATED SO THAT NO HARM TO HUMAN BODY BY TOUCHING AND INHALING WAS PREVENTED.  ALSO "NO FIRE" POSTER WAS PUT UP.  IN THE MEAN TIME, AD HOC COMMAND CENTER WAS ESTABLISHED IN NWA CARGO OFFICCE AND CONCERNED PARTIES WERE CONTACTED AS BELOW.   GOVERNMENT RELATED ORGANIZATIONS-JCAB AIRPORT OFFICE, CUSTOMS, AIRPORT AUTHORITY. TECHNICAL ORGANIZATION-DANGEROUS GOOD INFORMATION CENTER, EMERGENCY CONTACT (US WASHINGTON D.C.)  IN D\G SHIPPER'S DECLARATION.  SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE CONTACTED BY NWA BRUNCH OFFICE AT THEIR LOCATIONS.  WITH SUPPORT OF CONCERNED PARTIES THE INCIDENT WAS ENDED UP WITH NO INJURY TO PEOPLE AND NO DAMAGE TO FACILITY.  ALL THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID INCLUDING REMAINING IN THE DRUM WAS DISPOSED OF BY LICENSED INDUSTRIAL WASTE DISPOSING VENDOR MAY 02.  NWA STRONGLY REQUESTED IACT TO CONDUCT THE INTENSIVE TRAINING TO PREVENT THE ACCIDENT OF THIS NATURE FROM HAPPENIHNG WITH ENHANCED AWARENESS FOR D/G HANDLING.  IACT WILL REPORT OFFICIALY ABOUT THEIR COMPANY'S PREVENTIVE MEASURES IN WRITTEN.  WE WILL REPORT TO YOU ON RECEIPT.

LOCAL SUPERVISION PLACED PLASTIC SHEETING AND A BUCKET UNDER THE OUTLET.  ATSF RESPONDERS FOUND BOTTOM OUTLET TO BE FULLY CLOSED AND BOTTOM OUTLET CAP TO FULLY TIGHT. IT IS PRESUMED THAT THE VALVE MAY NOT HAVE BEEN FULLY CLOSED DURING LOADING.  DUE TO THE DETERIORATED GASKET, THIS PRODUCT DRIPPED.

column168: ON APRIL 22, 1996, PAT MCDONALD (DRIVER) LOADED HIS TRUCK FOR DEKALB.  NO LEAKS WERE PRESENT AT THAT TIME.  HE LEFT THE CHEROKEE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30PM.  PAT TOOK AN ALTERNATE ROUTE (2ND ST. CHEROKEE-DEKALB-PRESIDENT) DUE TO THE CONSTRUCTION AT BROADWAY.  THIS ROUTE IS MORE ROUGH AND JARRING THAN 2ND ST.  PAT ARRIVED AT THE DEKALB GATE.  WHILE WAITING FOR THE GATE TO BE OPENED, HE NOTICED STEAM IN HIS SIDE MIRROR.  WHEN HE OPENED THE DOOR TO GET OUT, HE INHALED THE HCL FUMES THAT WERE BEING BLOWN IN HIS DIRECTION BY THE WIND. PAT STATED THAT HE KNEW RIGHT AWAY WHAT THE FUMES WERE. HE GRABBED HIS SHIPPING PAPERS AND GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK, PUT THE SHIPPING PAPERS ON THE BUMPER AND DISENGAGED THE SECONDARY LATCH FOR THE ERT TEAM.  FUMES WERE SPEWING OUT AROUND THE REAR DOOR.  PAT INHALED FUMES A SECOND TIME.  PAT MADE HIS WAY TO THE GUARD SHACK AND DIALED THE EMERGENCY NUMBER AT APPROXIMATELY 12:40 P.M. ERT MEMBERS WERE AT THE SITE MOMENTARILY.  RICH KLASS ASSUMED THE IC ROLE. INITIALLY SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS THROWN ON THE STREET, AROUND THE TRUCK AND ON THE FUEL TANK.  THE TRUCK WAS BROUGHT ON SITE.  ERT MEMBERS BEGAN HOSING DOWN THE TRUCK AS WELL AS PUTTING DOWN MORE SODIUM BICARBONATE ON THE STREET.  THE TRUCK WAS UNLOADED UP TO THE LEAKING PALLET AND ALL MATERIAL WAS DECONTAMINATED.  THE HCL PALLET WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRUCK. THE ONE LEAKING DRUM WAS PULLED OFF THE PALLET AND PLACED IN AN OVERPACK CONTAINER WHICH WAS PLACED IN THE K-4 HOOD.  THE TWO REMAINING GOOD DRUMS WERE DECONTAMINATED AND PUT IN THE K-4 HOOD ALSO WHILE MASSIVE AMOUNTS OF SODIUM BICARBONATE WERE BEING DUMPED ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  THE SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS HOSED DOWN AND SPREAD TO THE FRONT OF THE TRUCK BOX IN ORDER TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  THE TRUCK WAS BACKED INTO K-DOCK WHERE IT WAS HOSED DOWN SOME MORE. THE BALANCE OF MATERIAL WAS UNLOADED AND HOSED DOWN.  THE TRUCK WAS HOSED DOWN INSIDE AND OUT, THEN THE BOX WAS SATURATED WITH A SODIUM BICARBONATE SOLUTION AND LEFT TO SIT OVERNIGHT. NO FURTHER INJURIES (OTHER THAN PAT) OCCURRED.  THE PROVISIONAL ALL CLEAR WAS GIVEN AFTER TWO HOURS.  NOTE ALL HCL RESIDUE WAS NEUTRALIZED THROUGH SIGMA'S WASTEWATER NEUTRALIZATION SYSTEM. THE PROBABLE OF THE LEAKING HCL DRUM IS A NAIL PUNCTURE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  WHEN THE NAIL PUNCTURED THE DRUM IS UNRESOLVED.  WE CAN SPECULATE THAT THE DRUMS SHIFTED ON THE TRUCK AT SOME POINT BETWEEN THE LOADING DOCK AT CHEROKEE AND THE DEKALB GATE AT PRESIDENT STREET.  WE DO KNOW FOR CERTAIN THAT THE DRUM WAS NOT LEAKING IN THE STAGING AREA AT CHEROKEE PRIOR TO LOADING.  THE PALLET BEING TRANSPORTED WAS A NEW PALLET BOUGHT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SIGMA SPECIFICATIONS.  THE NAIL HEADS PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLET WERE ALL LESS THAN A DIME'S THICKNESS IN HEIGHT.  IT APPEARS THE DRUM MAY HAVE BEEN FAULTY.  THE DRUM POLY WALL THICKNESS AT THE EDGE OF THE BASE OF THE DRUM WAS INADEQUATE AS IT APPEARED TO BE THINNER AT THE SEAM THAN REQUIRED. THE DRUM APPEARED TO BE USED OR RECONDITIONED.  WE

22 DRUMS LOADED IN NOSE OF TRAILER AND 34 DRUMS IN REAR OF TRAILER.  ON MOVING UNIT, AFTER IT WAS LOADED, DRUMS IN REAR CAME LOOSE FROM THEIR STRAPS AND SLID FORWARD, WITH FIVE (5) DRUMS RUPTURING/CRACKING FROM IMPACT WITH OTHER DRUMS.  TRAILERS EQUIPPED WITH A CONTAINMENT SYSTEM, AND A MINIMAL AMOUNT DRIPPED TO GROUND (LESS THAN 100 ML).  RESPONSE TEAM REMOVED DRUMS, CLEANED UP RELEASED PRODUCT AND DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER, PRIOR TO ITS RELEASE.

ON HOOKING UP TO UNLOAD, DRIVER REVERSED THIS PRODUCT HOSES AND PULLED PRODUCT OUT OF STORAGE, INTO THE TRAILER, CAUSING TRAILER TO OVERFLOW. PRODUCT HELD IN CONTAINMENT AREA AND PLACED INTO DRUMS BY FACIILITY PERSONNEL FOR DISPOSAL.  DELIVERY THEN COMPLETED WITHOUT INCIDENT.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM SPIRNG GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED FOR A ROUTINE COMFORT STOP AND DISOCVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF THIS MATERIAL ESCAPED ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA WHERE THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PLACED A CONTAINMENT PAIL UNDER THE VEHICLE AND CONTACTED THE HOME DISPATCHER.  THE DRIVER'S DISPATCHER DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CREW TO THE SCENE IN ORDER TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL SPILL DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER' LOCATION,  ALL CONTAINER WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM VISHAY INCORPORATED LOCATED AT 5900 AUSTRALIAN AVENUE IN WEST PALM BEACH FL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRIATOL, CT.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE. INC.  LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN ORDER TO TRANSFER THE CONTAINERS FROM ONE VEHICLE TO ANOTHER FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  DURING THE TRANSFER OPERATIONS ONE CONTAINER FELL FROM THE FORK-ILFT ONTO THE CEMENT DOCK AREA CAUSING THE CLOSURE TO DISLODGE RELEASING THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM TO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND A CONTAINMENT SUMP.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY INITIATED RESPONSE ACTIVITIES TO RECONTAINERIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND CLEAN THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND SUMP.  ALL SPILL DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND OF THE INCIDENT FOUND THAT THE DOCK PLATE DID NOT SIT FLUSH WITH THE FLOOR. WHEN THE FORK-LIFT WAS DRIVEN ACROSS THIS PLATE, THE PALLET OF DRUMS BEING MOVED SHIFTED ALLOWING ONE DRUM TO FALL AND OPEN.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE DOCK PLATE WILL BE PLACED FLUSH WITH THE LOADING DOCK TO PREVENT EXCESSIVE MOVEMENT WHEN THE FORK LIFT IS DRIVEN OVER THE PLATE.  PLEASE NOTE THAT THIS EVENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND WAS ASSIGNED INCIDENT #339018.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: A DUMP TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM MILES, INC. LOCATED AT 8500 WEST BAY ROAD IN BAYTOWN, TEXAS TO CLEAN HARBORS TECHNOLOGY CORP. LOCATED 5 MILES SOUTH ON HIGHWAY 71 IN KIMBALL, NE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE REAR DOOR ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY MOVED THE VEHICLE ONTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT WHERE THE SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED AND PROCESSED. IN ADDITION, ALL FREE LIQUIDS WERE ABSORBED WITH SPEEDY DRI AND DISPOSED OF AT THE DIPSOAL FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. AN INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT INDICATED THAT THE PROBABLE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE COULD BE ATTRIBUTED TO THE COLLECTION OF RAINWATER AT THE REAR DOOR OF THE VEHICLE.  THIS LIQUID ESCAPED THROUGH THE REAR SEAL OF THE DUMP TRAILER.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF RESIDUAL LIQUID WAS OBSERVED.  IN ADDITION, ALL CLOSURES WERE SECURED AND IN PLACE.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRANCE, LOADING PERSONNEL WILL BE RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT A LAYER OF A SUITABLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL IS PLACED AT THE REAR DOOR OF EACH DUMP TRAILER TO ABSORB ANY FREE LIQUIDS THAT COULD ACCUMLATE IN THIS LOCATION. DRIVERS WILL ALSO CONTINUE TO INSPECT ALL CLOSURE DEVICES AND REPLACE ANY COMPONENTS THAT ARE NOT IN PROPER WORKING ORDER.
column172: Highway hopper trailer for solid materials only

column168: A CARGO TANK WAS DDISPATCHED TO PERCEPTIVE BIOSYSTEMS LOCATED AT 251 ALBANY STREET IN CAMBRIDGE, MA IN ORDER TO PICK UP A SHIPMENT OF NON HAZARDOUS NON DOT REGULATED RINSE WATER FOR DISPOSAL.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SITE, THE DRIVER SET UP THE EQUIPMENT NECESSARY TO INITIATE THE LOADING PROCEDURES. AS SOON AS THE LOADING OPERATIONS WAS STARTED, A GASKET ON THE TRAILER VALVE FAILED ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE ONTO THE ASPHALT LOADING AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE LOADING OPERATION AND CLOSED ALL VALVES ON THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER THEN CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND NOTIFIED HIS HOME DISPATCHER OF THE INCIDENT. THE DRIVERS DISPATCHER DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CREW TO THE SCENE IN ORDER TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE RESPONSE CREW IDENTIFIED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF RESIDUAL PETROLEUM OIL THAT HAD REMAINED IN THE PUMP MECHANISM FROM A PREVIOUS LOAD HAD BEEN RELEASED ALONG WITH THE RINSE WATER WHEN THE GASKET FAILED. THE PETROLEUM OIL ALONG WITH THE RINSE WATER WAS ABSORBED WITH A SUITABLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED IN 2 X 55 GALLON DRUMS. THIS MATERIAL WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE VEHICLES USED IN CLEAN HARBORS WASTE OIL OPERATIONS HAVE HAD ALL GASKETS REPLACED.  PLEASE NOTE THAT ALL VEHICLES ARE SUBJECT TO REQUIRED INSPECTIONS AND TESTS.  THE VEHICLE INVOLVE IN THIS INCIDENT WAS CURRENT WITH ALL ITS REQUIRED INSPECTIONS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRUCK WAS EAST BOUND ON SR-4 NEAR LOS ALAMOS, NM, GOING UP A CROWN IN THE ROADWAY AT 40 MPH.  SR-4 ENDS IN A T INTERSECTION WITH EAST JEMEZ ROAD. THE DRIVER CLAIMED THE BRAKES FAILED WHEN HE APPLIED THEM, SO HE TURNED RIGHT TO AVOID A COLLISION.  THE TRUCK ROLLED COMPLETELY OVER, LANDING ON ITS WHEEL AT THE INTERSECTION.  AS IT ROLLED, A LIGHT POLE PUNCTURED THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANK SPILLING ABOUT 3,000 GALLONS OF OIL.  IT THEN ROLLED BACKWARD OVER A CAR WHICH WAS STOPPED AT THE INTERSECTION, FORCING IT UP ONTO AN EMBANKMENT.  EMERGENCY CREWS AT THE SCENE DIKED THE OIL IN A DITCH AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.  OUR OFFICE NOTIFIED EPA AND A LOCAL HAZ MAT CLEANUP SERVICE TO PROCEED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SITE.  WE WERE IN CONTACT WITH LOCAL OFFICAILS TO INFORM THEM OF OUR ACTIONS.

REEDER REMOVED SEAL TOTAL PETROLEUM 38688 AND OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS COMPLETELY COVERED WITH A HEAVY LAYER OF FROST.  THERE WAS NO SOUND OR ODOR COMING FROM THE VALVE.  NO LEAK WAS DETECTED USING LEAK DETECTING LIQUID.  THE CAR HAD 10" OUTAGE AND 180PSI PRESSURE.  NOT FINDING ANY LEAK, REEDER HAD THE CREW COUPLE INTO THE CAR AND SHAKE IT, HOPING TO CAUSE ANOTHER RELEASE.  NO RELEASE OCCURRED.  THE CAR WAS AGAIN INSPECTED AND NO EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.   CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

THE MSDS WILL BE INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT.  THE MSDS CLASSIFIES THIS PRODUCT AS FLAMMABLE GRS, 2.1, UN1037.  THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR ATTACHMENTS WITH THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  PROPER CERTIFICATION FOR TRANSPORT WILL BE OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER UPON RELEASE FROM THE FAA.  TOTAL AMOUNT OF ETHYL CHLORIDE SHIPPED: 24 OUNCES.  TOTAL AMOUNT OF ETHYL CHLORIDE SHIPPED: 8 OUNCES.

column168: ON APRIL 29, 1996 AT 5:00PM., OUR LEASE DRIVER DAVID RALEY HAD A SPILL AT 6924 MARLBORO PIKE, FORESTVILLE, MD.  AT THE PENN MAR SERVICE STATION. OUR LEASE DRIVER WAS PULLING OUR TRAILER 27.  HE ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION AND PROCEDED TO DROP HIS LOAD OF GASOLINE.  HE USED IMPROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  FIRST HE USED A COAXLE FITTING WHEN HE SHOULD HAVE USED A ONE ARM BANDIT AND A SEPARATE VAPOR FITTING.  HE CONTINUED UNLOADING.  WHILE UNLOADING HE DID NOT HAVE THE CAP TO THE VAPOR ON.  HE ALSO DIDN'T CHECK THE TANK SIZE PROPERLY.  LASTLY HE DID NOT STAY WITH THE TRUCK.  HE WENT INSIDE THE STORE.  WHILE IN THE STORE THE MANAGER SMELLED GAS AND RAN OUTSIDE.  HE COULD NOT FIND OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY.  OUR DRIVER RAN TO THE TRUCK, BY NOW APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS HAD OVERFLOWED FROM THE VAPOR OUTLET.  HE SHUT EVERYTHING OFF.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY.  HE TRIED TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL WITH WHAT HE HAD.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, E.P.A. AND COMPANY OFFICIALS ARRIVED WITHIN THE HOUR.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND DID NOT GO INTO ANY SEWER DRAINS.  OUR  COMPANY THEN CLEANED THE REMAINDER OF THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT, BROOMS AND SHOVELS.  DAVID RALEY HAS BEEN PROPERLY TRAINED BY OUR COMPANY AND KNOWINGLY BROKE THE RULES.  WHEN CONFRONTED HE ACTED LIKE HE DIDN'T KNOW ANY BETTER.  DUE TO THIS INCIDENT OUR COMPANY HAS ARRANGED AN IMMEDIATE SAFETY MEETING.  ALL SUPERVISORS ARE CHECKING EACH DRIVER INDIVIDUALLY ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  ANY PERSON NOT PASSING OUR CHECKLIST WILL BE PUT BACK INTO TRAINING.  ALONG WITH PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES ALL SAFETY TOPICS WILL BE REINFORCCED ONCE AGAIN.  DAVID RALEY HAS SINCE HAD HIS TRUCK INSPECTED, AND OUR TRAILER IS NOW AT FAIRFIELD GETTING INSPECTED. DAVID RALEY HAS BEEN FORMALLY REPRIMANDED, WRITTEN & VERBAL.  HE HAS ALSO BEEN SUSPENDED FOR ONE WEEK FOR WALKING AWAY FROM HIS TRUCK.  AFTER HIS SUSPENSION HE WILL BE PUT BACK INTO TRAINING.   WE WOULD LIKE TO TAKE THIS TIME TO THANK EVERYONE INVOLVED FOR THEIR IMMEDIATE ATTENTION TO THIS INCIDENT, AND WE ARE VEY SORRY FOR EVERYONES INCONVENIENCE.   HARDESTY & SON, INC. TAKES THIS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT VERY SERIOUSLY, AND WE ARE DOING EVERYTHING TO ENSURE THIS NEVER HAPPENS AGAIN.

column168: RONALD ANDREWS (#045235) ASHLAND CHEMICAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DRIVER FROM SOUTH BEND, IN ON HIS FIRST STOP PICKED UP 3 DRUMS (@1500#) (WPS# 9505-04438) OF A: RQ WASTE PAINT RELATED MATERIAL; 3 (FLAMMABLE LIQUID); UN1263 PGII (D001,F003,F005) FROM: (GENERATOR) DANVILLE STEEL DIVISION (MERVIS INDUSTRIES) 222 E GATE DRIVE DANVILLE, IL 61834.  THE DRUMS WERE LOADED ON THE TRUCK BY THE GENERATOR AFTER THE CORRECT LABELS, MARKINGS AND CONTAINERS WERE CHECKED.  THE MANIFEST (INA 1183566-ATTACHED) WAS SIGNED OFF BY THE GENERATOR'S REPRESENTATIVE (STEVE MARTENS) LOAD WAS SECURED AND VEHICLE LEFT THE SITE. ********** 6:55 A.M.  WHILE TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON 1-74, @ MILE MARKER I96, (6-8 MILES WEST OF DANVILLE PICKUP) OUR DRIVER (RON ANDREWS) RECEIVED A CALL ON THE C.B. FROM THE TRACTOR TRAILER BEHIND HIM NOTIFYING HIM THERE WAS A REDDISH/BROWN LIQUID GOING UP HIS BACK TRAILER DOOR (WAS VERY WINDY AND RAINING HARD).  RON PULLED OVER TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION, THERE WAS FOUND TO BE A PIN HOLE LEAK IN ONE OF THE DRUMS FROM DANVILLE STEEL.  ABSORBANT PADS AND FLOOR DRI WERE PLACED AROUND THE DRUM, AND ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, THE DRUM WAS THEN PUT INTO AN OVERPACK ALONG WITH THE PADS AND FLOOR DRI. APPROXIMATE LOSS FROM DRUM 4-5 GALLONS, 3-4 GALLONS CONTAINED IN PADS AND FLOOR DRI ON TRAILER. ****** 7:20 A.M.  RON CALLED INTO THE OFFICE, INFORMED BILL FITZSIMMONS (ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DISTRICT MANAGER) OF THE INCIDENT AND SECURED CONTAINER, THEN PROCEEDED TO NEXT PICKUP. ******* 7:35 A.M.  BILL FITZSIMMONS CONTACTED ERIC SPALSBURY (4362) EXPLAINED SITUATION.  * SPILL NO RQ LESS THAN 100# (@ 1 GALLON LEAKED OUTSIDE TRAILER) * PIN HOLE IN DRUM * VERY WINDY AND RAINING HARD * ACCUMULATE FACTS AND CALL 1-800 ASHLAND TO REPORT. ********** 12:10 P.M.  ONCE ALL FACTS IN, CALLED 1-800-ASHLAND AND TALKED TO LYNNE, GAVE ALL FACTS. ******* 12:15 P.M.  CALLED GENERATOR STEVE LATHAM 217-442-5300 (EXT. 222), OUT OF TOWN UNTIL WEDNESDAY APRIL 24, 1996.  CONTACTED STEVE MARTENS (DANVILLE STEEL - FABRICATION DEPT.) AND INFORMED HIM OF SITUATION.  HE DIDN'T LOAD IT BUT DID SIGN THE MANIFEST. ********** 1:15 P.M.  RECEIVED CALL FROM MARK METCALF EH & S TO REVIEW FACTS AND INFORM THAT D.O.T. 5800.1 REPORT MUST BE SUBMITTED.  ****** FUTURE PREVENTION:  DOUBLE AND TRIPLE CHECK ALL CONTAINERS VS. DRIVERS CHECKLIST.  POOR INTEGRITY CONTAINERS NEED TO BE REPACKAGED OR OVERPACKED BEFORE TRANSPORTATION.

I, KAREN NICHOLS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR., WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A SHIPMENT OF GASOLINE THAT WAS EMITTING A STRONG GASOLINE ODOR.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A 4G SPECIFICATION FIBERBOARD BOX WHICH WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND DECLARED FOR GASOLINE.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX, I FOUND 3 X 1 QUART, GLASS BOTTLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  THESE PLASTIC CLOSURES WERE SECURED WITH TAPE. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: INQUIRIES ABOUT A POSSIBLE ACCIDENT INVOLVING AN ADM VEHICLE WERE RECEIVED BY THIS OFFICE AT AROUND 15:10, MONDAY, APRIL 29,1996.  FIRST REPORTS OF AN ACCIDENT WERE RECEIVED VIA GENE SMITH, ADM CORPORATE LOSS PREVENTION, FROM THE BENTON COUNTY, IOWA, SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT DISPATCH.  INFORMATION WAS INITIALLY VERY SKETCHY.  ALL THAT WAS KNOWN WAS THAT A TRACTOR- TRAILER HAD ROLLED OVER ON NORTHBOUND I-380,NORTH OF CEDAR RAPIDS, IOWA. THIS OFFICE CONTACTED ADM TRUCKING, IN CEDAR RAPIDS,  TO SEE IF THEY HAD RECEIVED ANY REPORTS OF TROUBLE.  THEY INDICATED THEY HAD NOT, BUT INFORMED US THAT THEIR DRIVER, DON L. STRAIT, HAD LEFT ON DISPATCH WITHIN THE LAST HOUR AND WAS HEADED IN THAT DIRECTION.  CONFIRMATION THAT IT WAS OUR UNIT, AND THAT MR. STRAIT WAS THE DRIVER, CAME SHORTLY AFTER OUR INITIAL INQUIRIES, THROUGH MR. SMITH.  AT THIS TIME, MR. SMITH SUPPLIED US WITH THE PHONE NUMBER FOR BENTON COUNTY SHERIFF AND OUR INVESTIGATION BEGAN IN EARNEST.  THE ACCIDENT HAD OCCURRED AT AROUND 14:39, AS ADM TRACTOR #095288, PULLING ALCOHOL TRAILER #A91243, WITH A PAYLOAD OF 8101 GALLONS, WAS NORTHBOUND ON I-380, NEARING MILEMARKER 46, NORTH OF URBANA, IOWA.  THE UNIT APPARENTLY RAN OFF THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE AND OVERTURNED IN A DITCH.  FIRST REPORTS INDICATED THAT THE DRIVER WAS INJURED AND THE TRAILER HAD A HOLE IN IT AND WAS LEAKING DENATURED ALCOHOL, 3, NA1987, II (FUEL ALCOHOL) ONTO THE SURROUNDING GROUND.  THE INTERSTATE HAD BEEN COMPLETELY SHUT DOWN AND THE ENTIRE AREA WAS SECURED BY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS AND THE IOWA STATE PATROL.  FIRST CONTACT WITH ANYONE AT THE SCENE WAS WITH JEFF TILSON, ASSITANT DIRECTOR, BENTON COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT.  MR. TILSON INFORMED US THAT THE TRAILER HAD A HOLE, APPROXIMATELY THE SIZE OF A GARDEN HOSE, AND ALCOHOL WAS LEAKING OUT AT THE RATE OF ABOUT 1/2 GALLON PER MINUE.  WE WERE ALSO INFORMED THAT LINN COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY WAS SENDING A HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE.  STEPS WERE IN PROGRESS TO DISPATCH AN EMPTY ALCOHOL TRAILER TO THE SCENE FOR TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM THE OVERTURNED TRAILER. ADM TRUCKING, CEDAR RAPIDS HAD NO EQUIPMENT IMMEDIATELY AVAILABLE SO ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH ADM TRUCKING, CAMANCHE, IOWA, TO SEND A UNIT AND PERSONNEL TO ASSIST AT THE SCENE.  NOTIFICATION OF THE VARIOUS GOVERNMENT AGENCIES BEGAN WITH A CALL TO MARK ISHIHARA, ADM CORPORATE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERING SERVICES.  SUBSEQUENT CALLS WERE MADE, AND TELEPHONE REPORTS WERE FILED WITH THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (D.O.T.) AT 15:55, 04/29/96 (CASE #338879 AND THE IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES (E.P.A. )AT 16:12, 4/29/96 (SPILL #04296-KL-1615).  IOWA D.N.R'S KATHLEEN LEE SUPPLIED US WITH AN UPDATE FROM THE SCENE AT AROUND 16:45, RERPORTING THAT LINN COUNTY E.M.A. WAS WORKING TO SEAL THE HOLE IN THE TRAILER.  IOWA D.O.T. HAD DUMPED SAND IN THE DITCH TO HELP CONTAIN THE SPILL.  THE AREA WAS ENVELOPED IN STRONG VAPORS FROM THE SPILL.  A CALL WAS RECEIVED FROM STEVE FORD, SAFETY MANAGER, ADM, CEDAR R

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Overfilled
column168: DRIVER MARIO AMBROSIO WAS FILLING ECONOMY TANK FROM ONE FILL.  DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO GAUGE THE TANK HE WAS FILLING DUE TO SICK LINE COVER JAMMED. THE FILL CAP WAS LOOSE UNDER THE JAMMED CORNER, WHICH APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS SPILLED FROM THE TANK.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THE DRIVER WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS ON THE TRUCK AND CLEANED UP BY A PROFESSIONAL SPILL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR.  THE SPILL DID NOT ENTER ANY DRAINS OR REACH ANY SOILED

THE DRIVER WAS UNLAODING DIESEL IN AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  HE OBSERVED A SMALL LEAK IN THE HOSE FROM THE PUMP TO THE ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  THE DRIVER DISCONNECTED THE LINE BEFORE SHUTTING OFF THE DISCHARGE VALVE.  WHEN HE DISCONNECTED THE LINE, A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF FUEL OCCURRED.  THE DRIVER STARTED THE CLEANUP WITH HIS ON BOARD SPILL KIT, AND ALSO A TEAM FROM THE MISSION HST. OFFICE ARRIVED TO ASSIST WITH THE CLEAN UP.  THE PARKING LOT WILL HAVE TO BE REPLACE. THE ROOT CAUSE WAS THE DRIVER USED AN INCORRECT PROCEDURE WHEN UNLOADING AFTER DISCONNECTING THE LEAK.  THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN 7 DAYS OFF WITH OUT PAY AND WILL BE REQUIRED TO ATTEND THE NEXT TRAINING CLASS FOR MISSION DRIVER.

column62: Abrasion; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ACTING AT THE REQUEST OF HAPAG-LLOYD (AMERICA)INC. 555 EAST OCEAN BLVD., STE 300, LONG BEACH CALIFONIA, AND WITHOUT PREJUDICE, WE DID, ON APRIL 8, 1996, ATTEND AT THE US COAST GUARD OFFICE, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA. PURPOSE OF THE VARIOUS ATTENDENCE WAS TO DOCUMENT A HAZARDOUS CARGO LEAK, EX ONE (1) 20' CONTAINER.  SUBJECT TWO (2) CONTAINERS, HLCU 225473-6 AND HLCU 227944-1 , LOADED WITH A SHIPMENT OF EIGHTY (80) DRUMS EACH CONTAINING CRESOLS, WERE LOADED ONTO THE "NEPTUNE GARNET" IN NEW YORK, ON MARCH 24, 1996.  THEREAFTER, VESSEL TRANSITED NORFOLK AND SAVANNAH, PRIOR TO ARRIVING LOS ANGELES.  ON APRIL 2, 1996 AROUND APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS., A STRONG ODOR WAS DETECTED EMITTING FROM CONTAINER HLCU 225473-6. BOTH CONTAINERS WRE STOWED ABOVE DECK, AS FOLLOWS"  HLCU 225473-6 ON BAY 1, 2ND TIER, AND HLCU 2279744-1 ON BAY 3, BOTTOM TIER.  WE UNDERSTAND THAT VESSEL CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, PMC SPECIALISTIES, WHO CAUTIONED THE SHIPS CREW TO AVOID SKIN CONTACT WITH NOTED MATERIAL.  A TRICKLE WAS ALSO NOTED LEAKING FROM CONTAINER HLCU 225473-6.  A METAL BUCKET WAS PLACED BELOW THE LEAK AJACENT TO THE HATCH LID, IN ORDER TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  ALL CONCERNED PARTIES WERE NOTIFIED BY THE VESSEL.  ON APRIL 3, 1996, THE AREA WAS REINSPECTED AND IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED, HOWEVER, THERE WAS STILL A FAINT ODOR.  THE AMBIENT TEMPERAUTRE WAS ROUGHLY +30 DEG.C. (+86 DEG.F.)  THE OTHER CONTAINER HLCY 227944-1 WAS ALSO INSPECTED AND NO LEAK WAS FOUND.  WE UNDERSTAND THAT RESPIRATORS WERE USED BY THE SHIPS CREW AS NEEDE.  THE VESSLE'S ETA LOS ANGELES WAS APRIL 8, 1996, 2230 HRS.  APRIL 8, 1996 AT US COAST GUARD OFFICE, LONG BEACH CALIFORNIA.  ON THIS DATE, THE FOLLOWING PARTIES WERE PRESENT" LONG BEACH FIRE CHIEF MR. BADGETT ASSISTANT CHIEF MARINE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, MR. KEITH WHITEMAN OF THE US COAST GUARD AND VARIOUS OTHER US COAST GUARD OFFICIALS. PERSONNEL FROM ANCON MARINE, INC. (ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP COMPANY APPOINTED BY NEPTUNE ORIENTAL LINE TO CONDUCT THE NEEDED SERVICES).  MR. GREY BOROSSAY OF HAPAG-LLOYD (AMERICAN)INC.  MR. TOM SHERDIAN OF NATIONAL CARGO BUREAU AND MR. ANTHONY SWAMINATHAN OF ACKERMAN-SWAMINATHAN, INC., SURVEYORS, REPRESENTING HAPAG-LLOYD.  AT THE MEETING, THE VARIOUS ASPECTS OF THE LEAKAGE WERE DISCUSSED AND A TENATIVE PLAN OF ACTION WAS PREPARED. AT APPROXIMATELY 2330 HOURS, WE OBSERVED THE VESSEL APPRAOCHING THE BERTH. AT 2400 HRS THE VESSEL WAS IN THE TURNING BASIN.

column42: ENGINE STARTING FLUID, WITH FLAMMABLE GAS
column168: ON OPERATIONS DATE 04/02/96 P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS TAMMY FLORENCE AND ALAN HENDERSON WERE DISPATCHED TO INVESTIGATE A PACKAGE THAT WAS EMMITING AN ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL THE TWO P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS FOUND 11 BOXES OF A 16 LOT AND IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO OPEN THE BOXES.  ONLY TWO OF THE 11 BOXES OPENED WERE FOUND TO CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  DUE TO TIME CONSTRAINTS THE 11 BOXES WERE SENT TO THE HAZ MAT SORT FOR FURTHER INSPECTION TO BE SURE ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE FOUND, AND THE BOXES THAT ONLY CONTAINED CLOTHES AND OTHER HOUSEHOLD MATERIALS WERE MOVED ON TO THE PROPER DESTINATION.  ONE OF THE TWO BOXES THAT ENDED UP BEING HELD ONLY CONTAINED ONE 3.3 FLUID OUNCE OF (OSCAR DE LA RENTA) PERFUME IN A DECORATIVE BASKET. THE PERSON RESPONSIBLE FOR SHIPPING THE 16 BOXES STATED THAT THE RECEIVING PARTY NEEDED THE CLOTHES OUT OF ONE OF THE TWO BOXES WE WERE HOLDING, NAMELY THE BOX THAT CONTAINED THE OSCAR DE LA RENTA PERFUME, AND ASKED IF WE COULD CONTACT OUR LOCAL FEDERAL AVIATION INSPECTORS AND REQUEST THAT THE PERFUME BE REMOVED FROM THE BOX AND FORWARD ON THE CLOTHES IN THE BOX.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH SPECIAL AGENT CHUCK HIENRICH OF THE INDIANA, INDIANAPOLIS OFFICE AND HE STATED THAT THIS WOULD BE OKAY. HE WAS ADVISED THAT POLAROID PICTURES WOULD BE TAKEN OF THE PERFUME INSIDE THE BOX BEFORE MOVING THE BOX ON TO DESTINATION. ****** THE LAST BOX TO BE OPENED CONTAINED FINGERNAIL POLISH, REMOVER, AND OTHER BEAUTY CARE PRODUCTS, AS WELL AS CAR CARE PRODUCTS ALL OF WHICH WILL BE ITEMIZED BELOW: 1 X 3.3 FL. OZ. OF OSCAR DE LA RENTA PERFUME; 1 X 4.5 FL. OZ. DRY KWIK NATURAL SPRAY (FLAMMABLE PUMP SPRAY); 1 X 12.5 ML BRAUN STYLE SHAPER (BUTANE, UNDER PRESSURE); 1 X 1.8 FL. OZ. OF CLINIQUE HAIRSPRAY (FLAMMABLE PUMP SPRAY); 1 X .5 FL. OZ. OF CALCIUM GEL NAIL BUILDER (FLAMMABLE); 1 X .5 FL. OZ OF CUTEX CUTTICLE CARE (FLAMMABLE); 2 X .5 FL. OZ. EACH OF REVLON NAIL ENAMEL (FLAMMABLE); 2 X .5 FL. OZ. OF REVLON STRONG WEAR (FLAMMABLE); 1 X 22 FL. OZ. "TUFF STUFF" FOAM CLEANER (AEROSOL); 1 X 11 FL. OZ. OF KRYLON SPRAY PAINT (AEROSOL); 1 X 11 FL. OZ. OF WHEEL PAINT (AEROSOL); 2 X 11 FL. OZS. EACH OF ENGINE STARTING FLUID (AEROSOLS), ONE OF WHICH LEAKED.  ****** THIS SHIPMENT IS IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY, AND WILL REMAIN THERE UNTIL AN AGENT WITH THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION INVESTIGATES.  UPON RELEASE, THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO DESTINATION VIA HIGHWAY ACCORDING TO ALL APPLICABLE RULES AND REGULATIONS SET FORTH BY TITLE 49CFR.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2030 HOURS ON APRIL 29TH, A YARD CREW DISCOVERED TANK CAR GATX 43683 LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED FOR INSPECTION. KNOWLEDGEABLE EMPLOYEES ARRIVED AT 0800 THE FOLLOWING DAY AND FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE LOOSE GAUGING DEVICE PROTECTIVE COVER WITH AN ICE BUILD-UP.  WEATHER CONDITIONS PREVENTED THEM FROM EFFECTING REPAIRS AT THAT TIME.  CONRAIL'S FIELD HAZMAT MGR. T. DAVIS ARRIVED LATER THAT DAY AND CONFIRMED THEIR FINDINGS.  HE REMOVED THE GAUGING DEVICE COVER AND NOTED PRODUCT COMING OUT OF THE NEEDLE VALVE PLUG.  THE PLUG HAD A SMALL HOLE DRILLED THROUGH IT; THAT CONDITION COMBINED WITH THE NEEDLE VALVE BEING PARTLY OPEN ALLOWED THE LEAK.  MR. DAVIS CLOSED THE NEEDLE VALVE 1/4 TURN, STOPPING THE LEAK.  ALL CLOSURES WERE TIGHTENED AND EVERY FITTING CHECKED WITH A SOAPY WATER SOLUTION.  NO OTHER LEAKS WERE DETECTED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION AT 1845 HOURS.

UTCU 414785 NOTED EMITTING VAPORS BY SSW RAILWAY CONDUCTOR.  CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE.  FERGUSON-HARBOUR INC., RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED A LOOSE PACKING NUT ON THE LOADING VALVE. CONTAINER SAFE FOR MOVMENT.  ONE SSW CONDUCTOR AND FOUR NORFOLK SOUTHERN EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED TO PRODUCT VAPORS AND TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION.  ALL FIVE WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.  THE FOUR NS EMPLOYEES RETURNED TO WORK WITH NO LOST TIME.  THE SSW CONDUCTOR REMAINED OFF AS OF 4-30-96.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE THE CONTAINER WAS IN THE POSSESSION OF THE ST LOUIS AND SOUTHWESTERN RAILRAOD, BUT THE INCIDENT WAS ON NORFOLK SOUTHER PROPERTY.  ANY FURTHER INFORMATION REGARDING INJURIES OR DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT SHOULD BE DIRECTED TO IKE SEABAUGH, HAZMAT CONTROL OFFICER, SOUTHER PACIFIC RAILROAD, PINE BLUFF, ARKANSAS, TELEPHONE 501-541-1784.

ALLEN ESKRIDGE WITH HAPAG-LLOYD, HOUSTON SENT A MEMO DESCRIBING SITUATION.  NCB APPOINTED BY HAPAG-LLOYD TO INSPECT TANL 4 PREPARE INCIDENT REPORT.

THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL VARIOUS TYPES OF HOUSEHOLD CONSUMER GOODS INCLUDING VD-40, PAINT TIN, VIDEO/AUDIO CLEANER COOLANT, AND HYDRAULIC OIL. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACK SORT WHEN SLIGHT LEAKAGE AND ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL SEVERAL DIFFERENT TYPES OF HOUSEHOLD PRODUCT USED FOR CLEANING AND OTHER PURPOSES.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

PAIL LEAKED DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND PUT IN RECOVERY DRUM BY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHEN UNLOADING THE DRUMS FROM A STORAGE TRAILER THE DSR NOTICED THE FLOOR AROUND ONE DRUM WAS WET.  ONE DRUM HAD APPARENTLY BEEN HIT WHEN LOADED AND NOT NOTICED BY ANYONE.  THE SMALL DENT CAUSED A PIN HOLE LEAK WHICH THRU THE COURSE OF THE NITE HAD LEAKED APPOX 4 TO 60 OZ.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED, 513-731-3400, SUE MOORE, WHO ADVISED US ON THE PROPER CLEAN UP PROCEDURES, AND FAXED US AN MSDS.  THE DRUM WAS PUT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER ON PRO 876728510.
PETROMETER MALFUNCTIONED
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON 043096 AT APPROXIMATELY 530PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, STEVE DOLEAL THAT THIS CAR WAS LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  DOLEZAL MOVED THE CAR TO AN ISOLATED LOCATION FOR EMERGENCY REPAIRS.  WHEN  REEDER ARRIVED, HE NOTED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM AN AREA WHERE THE BOTTOM OUTLET SKID PROTECTION PLATE WAS WELDED TO THE CAR. REEDER USED PETRO PLUG TO TRY AND STOP THE LEAK.  THIS WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AS THE LEAK WAS INSIDE THE SKID PLATE.  A BUCKET WAS USED TO CATCH THE DRIPPING PRODUCT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND ASKED TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER, AMOCO OIL.  AN HOUR AND 20 MINUTES AFTER CALLING CHEMTREC, ROY LAMDEN OF AMOCO RETURNED REEDER'S CALL.  ALTHOUGH REEDER ACCURATELY DESCRIBED THE PROBLEM AND STATED THAT THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED, AMOCO WANTED TO PERSONALLY INSPECT THE CAR BEFORE ARRANGING FOR A TRANSFER.  LAMDEN ARRIVED AROUND 10PM AND QUICKLY AGREED WITH REEDERS DIAGNOSIS.  HE THEN CALLED EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO TRANSFER THE CAR INTO TRUCKS FOR RETURN TO THEIR FACILITY.  THE TRANSFER OPERATION WAS COMPLETED AT 8PM ON MAY 1, APPROXIMATELY 26 HOURS AFTER THE CAR WAS FIRST DISCOVERED LEAKING.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF TRAIN CYDE-17, EXTRA 2512, SOUTH, NOTED TANK CAR GATX 64124, PRODUCT LEAKING FROM MANWAY.  TWO OUT OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE IN DOWN OR OFF POSITION, THREE OUT OF EIGHT WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. PROPERLY SECURED MANWAY SWING BOLTS, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  JOE BABER, CHEMTREC, FILE 43430 AND GEOFF ASNES, CLEAN HARBORS, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT TANK CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A SAFETY VENT, TANK CAR WAS SET OUT OF TRAIN AND CLEAN HARBORS FILED FOR A DOT EMERGENCY EXEMPTION TO MOVE TANK CAR TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT. HENDERSON, COLORADO, FOR UNLOADING.  DOT APPROVED MOVEMENT UNDER EXEMPTION NUMBER DOT-E-11683, OF APRIL 19,1996.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF SOUTH THREE TRACK, CHEYENNE, NOTED FROST BUILD UP ON PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  ALSO, FROST BUILD UP ON RIGHT SIDE OF JACKET. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT INSIDE OF PROTECTIVE HOUSING THERE WAS A 2-INCH ICE BUILD-UP.  MGM 60 SERIES, GAUGING ROD, HAD 1/4 INCH ANGLE VALVE OPEN ONE FULL TURN WITH 1/4 INCH PLUG LAYING LOOSE ON GAUGING DEVICE FLANGE. ALSO, GAUGING ROD PACKING GLAND WAS LOOSE.  TOOK 3 FULL  TURNS ON PACKING GLAND NUT, AND SHUT OFF ANGLE VALVE AND PROPERLY SECURED 1/4 INCH PLUG, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT INTACT SEAL; CONOCO 124931, WAS APPLIED.  HAD TO REMOVE SEAL TO COMPLETE REPAIRS.  BOB WIBLE, CHEMTREC, FILE 43383 AND REX REDFERN, CONOCO, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW WAS NOTIFIED BY CAR FOREMAN THAT ONE SPOT CARMEN REPORTED A HISSING NOISE AND A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM TANKCAR NATX29939.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TWO BOLT PACKING GLAND ON STUFFING BOX OPERATED, BOTTOM VALVE WAS LOOSE.  REPACKED STUFFING BOX AND PROPERLY SECURED PACKING GLAND, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  WINDEL STWERT, COASTAL CHEM, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT INTACT SEAL:  UP J 162958, WAS REMOVED SO REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.

ON FRIDAY, APRIL 19, 1996 AT 1140 HOURS, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT E.R. FREDERICK, WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANKCAR GATX 14580 WAS IN THE ALEXANDRIA, LA. YARD AND IT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  HE WAS ALSO ADVISED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN PLACED IN A SECLUDED LOCATION, PENDING HIS INSPECTION.  CTS REGIONAL MANAGER, TOM ROBINSON WAS ADVISED.  SAHM FEDERICK WAS MET AT THE SCENE BY REGIONAL MANAGER ROBINSON, SPECIAL AGENT HERRING, DEQ REPRESENTATIVE BOBBY LAMBRIGHT, AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZMAT OFFICER RICHARD ORTEGO.  THE CAR WAS INSPECTED.  IT APPEARED TO HAVE A SMALL AMOUNT OF COMMODITY RESIDUE ON THETOP AND THE SIDES OF THE TANK.  THE SPILLAGE APPEARED TO BE OLD, AND APPEARED TO HAVE COME FROM THE SAFEY RELIEF VALVE.  INSPECTION FURTHER INDICATED THAT THE CAR HAD PROPER OUTAGE AND WAS OTHERWISE SECURE FOR SHIPMENT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION. MR. ROGER REYNOLDS, SUPERVISOR OF TRANSPORTATION ADMINISTRATION FOR MERICHEM WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF ALL OF THE DETAILS CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT.  REYNOLDS ADVISED THAT AFTER THE CAR WAS UNLOADED, HE WOULD HAVE IT INSPECTED WITH SPECIAL ATTENTION GIVEN TO THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.

REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED THAT CREW REPORTED THE STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR CAR ACFX 18604.  ON GROUND INSPECTION DEVELOPED SEAL BN INC IG-974715" PROTECTING THE COVER PLATE.  REMOVED SEAL AND FOUND LIQUID SEEPING FROM THE BASE OF THE A END LIQUID VALVE, LEFT SIDE OF BASE. TIGHTENED THE TWO LEFT SIDE NUTS THAT SECURE THE VALVE AND LEAK STOPPED. CAR HAS 19 1/2 INCHES OUTAGE AT 120 PSI.  MR. ROBERT BROWNING AND IVAN DUNSWORTH OF FARMLAND ENID PLANT ALSO RESPONDED AND INSPECTED CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  SEAL BN INC IG-973993 WAS APPLIED.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY D.A. LOW, WAS NOTIFIED BY CAR DEPARTMENT, RIP TRACKS, CHEYENNE, THAT A PUNGENT ODOR WAS COMING FROM TANK CAR NATX 29167.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TWO OUT OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT MANWAY GASKET WAS MISSING.  APPLIED GOR-TEX SEAL AND PROPERLY SECURED MANWAY SWING BOLTS, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  JEFF BOTWINICK, CHEMTREC, FILE 43542, MILLEY RIVERA, KERN OIL AND ALICE MARTIN, COASTAL CHEM, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

AT 1400 HR. ON SUNDAY THE 21ST DAY OF APRIL, MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY THE OGDEN M.T.O. REGARDING A LEAKING CAR, LOCATED ON ICE HOUSE 9.  FIRE DEPT. NOTIFIED BY  CONCERNED CITIZEN, FIRE DEPT REMAINED ON STAND BY.  INSPECTION REVEALED CAR LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE PACKING ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET CONTROL ROD.  IT WAS NECESSARY TO REPACK THE HOUSING WITH GORTEX, AND THE RETAINER WAS TIGHTENED.  TASK COMPLETED AT 1520 HRS, CAR RELEASED AND CHEMTREC INFORMED ASSIGNED CASE 43583.  SHIPPER ALSO NOTIFIED.

column168: SAHM LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAILER REAZ 638551 WAS NOTED WITH A STRONG ODOR NEAR THE NOSE.  HOWEVER, NO LIQUID LEAK HAD BEEN DETECTED.  EXTERIOR INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER REAZ 638551 AND FLATCAR CP 504337 WERE BOTH NOTED TO BE DRY REFLECTING NO EVIDENCE OF A LIQUID LEAK.  STILL A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  HOWEVER COULD NOT DETECT ANY FLAMMABLE VAPOR WITH THE GAS TRAC.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THIS TRAILER CONTAINED 7 DIFFERENT PRODUCTS, SIX OF WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THE INTERIOR INSPECTION NOTED AN INCREASE IN THE VOLUME OF THE GAS TRAC, WHEN THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED.  HOWEVER, THE LIGHT SCALE NEVER CHANGED FROM GREEN.  FURTHER, INTERIOR INSPECTION NOTED SEVERAL 55 GALLON METAL AND PLASTIC DRUMS TO BE LEAKING AT THE BUNG CLOSURE WITH SMALL QUANTITIES OF THE RESPECTIVE PRODUCTS CONFINED TO THE TOP PORTION OF THE DRUMS. LIBBY CONTACTED MIKE HEADLEY, PETROLITE, PASADENA, TEXAS, WHO IN TURN CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH PAUL SCHMIDT, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SEATTLE TO SECURE THE LOOSE BUNGS AND WIPE THE DRUMS IN QUESTION.  PRODUCT ID CRWO 12F, CRWO 1541, DMO-4195G, PAD-0033E, WELLAID-0839L, X-CIDE-01024.  DOT ID ALCOHOL METHANOL, SODIUM NITRATE, FLAMMABLE NAPTHA, NAPTHA ETHYLHEXANOL, ALCOHOL (METHANOL), ALCOHOL (ISOPROPANOL), DRUMS 24, 1, 6, 30, 11, 12, LEAKERS, 11,1, 6, 5+1, 8, 11, 55 GAL DRUM TYPE METAL, METAL, METAL, METAL, PLASTIC, PLASTIC. PLEASE NOTE THAT 1 METAL DRUM OF PAD-0033E, BILLED AS FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. (CONTAINES AROMATIC NAPTHA AND 2-ETHYLHEXANOL) CLASS 3, UN1993, PG 111 WAS LOCATED IN THE 1ST ROW CENTER (NOSE) OF TRAILER REAZ 638511 WAS COMPLETELY EMPTY OF PRODUCT.  THE BOTTOM WELD SEAM WAS RUBBED AND ABRADED, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO COMPLETELY EMPTY WHILE ENROUTE.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS NOTED WITH A SMALL 8 INCH WET SPOT UNDER THE DRUM, WHICH WAS WIPED DRY.  THE BUNG WAS SECURED AND THE DRUM WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE TRAILER UPSIDE DOWN IN ITS ORIGINAL LOCATION. TRAILER REAZ 638551 WAS LOADED WITH A TOTAL OF 84 DRUMS AND NOTED WITH A TOTAL OF 43 DRUMS WITH LOOSE BUNG CLOSURES.  IT ALSO SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THESE BUNGS WERE 3" IN DIA. WITH A 1" PLUG IN THE CENTER ALSO NOTED LOOSE. ADDITIONAL BLOCKING AND BRACING TOO WERE ADDED TO THE TRAILER, HOWEVER, THIS DID NOT APPEAR TO BE A FACTOR WITH THE EMPTY DRUM THAT HAD LEAKED. column168: SAHM LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAILER REAZ 638551 WAS NOTED WITH A STRONG ODOR NEAR THE NOSE.  HOWEVER, NO LIQUID LEAK HAD BEEN DETECTED.  EXTERIOR INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER REAZ 638551 AND FLATCAR CP 504337 WERE BOTH NOTED TO BE DRY REFLECTING NO EVIDENCE OF A LIQUID LEAK.  STILL A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  HOWEVER COULD NOT DETECT ANY FLAMMABLE VAPOR WITH THE GAS TRAC.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THIS TRAILER CONTAINED 7 DIFFERENT PRODUCTS, SIX OF WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THE INTERIOR INSPECTION NOTED AN INCREASE IN THE VOLUME OF THE GAS TRAC, WHEN THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED.  HOWEVER, THE LIGHT SCALE NEVER CHANGED FROM GREEN.  FURTHER, INTERIOR INSPECTION NOTED SEVERAL 55 GALLON METAL AND PLASTIC DRUMS TO BE LEAKING AT THE BUNG CLOSURE WITH SMALL QUANTITIES OF THE RESPECTIVE PRODUCTS CONFINED TO THE TOP PORTION OF THE DRUMS. LIBBY CONTACTED MIKE HEADLEY, PETROLITE, PASADENA, TEXAS, WHO IN TURN CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH PAUL SCHMIDT, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SEATTLE TO SECURE THE LOOSE BUNGS AND WIPE THE DRUMS IN QUESTION.  PRODUCT ID CRWO 12F, CRWO 1541, DMO-4195G, PAD-0033E, WELLAID-0839L, X-CIDE-01024.  DOT ID ALCOHOL METHANOL, SODIUM NITRATE, FLAMMABLE NAPTHA, NAPTHA ETHYLHEXANOL, ALCOHOL (METHANOL), ALCOHOL (ISOPROPANOL), DRUMS 24, 1, 6, 30, 11, 12, LEAKERS, 11,1, 6, 5+1, 8, 11, 55 GAL DRUM TYPE METAL, METAL, METAL, METAL, PLASTIC, PLASTIC. PLEASE NOTE THAT 1 METAL DRUM OF PAD-0033E, BILLED AS FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. (CONTAINES AROMATIC NAPTHA AND 2-ETHYLHEXANOL) CLASS 3, UN1993, PG 111 WAS LOCATED IN THE 1ST ROW CENTER (NOSE) OF TRAILER REAZ 638511 WAS COMPLETELY EMPTY OF PRODUCT.  THE BOTTOM WELD SEAM WAS RUBBED AND ABRADED, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO COMPLETELY EMPTY WHILE ENROUTE.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS NOTED WITH A SMALL 8 INCH WET SPOT UNDER THE DRUM, WHICH WAS WIPED DRY.  THE BUNG WAS SECURED AND THE DRUM WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE TRAILER UPSIDE DOWN IN ITS ORIGINAL LOCATION. TRAILER REAZ 638551 WAS LOADED WITH A TOTAL OF 84 DRUMS AND NOTED WITH A TOTAL OF 43 DRUMS WITH LOOSE BUNG CLOSURES.  IT ALSO SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THESE BUNGS WERE 3" IN DIA. WITH A 1" PLUG IN THE CENTER ALSO NOTED LOOSE. ADDITIONAL BLOCKING AND BRACING TOO WERE ADDED TO THE TRAILER, HOWEVER, THIS DID NOT APPEAR TO BE A FACTOR WITH THE EMPTY DRUM THAT HAD LEAKED. column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER CTS WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TANK CAR WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION.  CAR GATX 7224, WAS RECEIVED ON INTERCHANGE FROM THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD AT COLTON, 1045 HOURS, SUNDAY, APRIL 21, 1996, AND ARRIVED YERMO IN THE CNYR-20, AT 1700 HOURS. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND ASSEMBLY WITH BAFFLE, WHICH IS MOUNTED ON THE MANWAY PLATE ADJACENT TO THE QUICK FILL HOLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND BS & B STAINLESS/TEFLON FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTING WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE  TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES; THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION; AND THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

TOOK ONE AND ONE QUARTER TURNS ON PACKING GLANDS, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  LAURA RUSHIN, CONCO, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EXCEPTION.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT SEAL CONOCO 125759 WAS REMOVED SO REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW WAS NOTIFIED BY CAR DEPARTMENT, DENVER, THAT TANK CAR UTLX 13304, HAD PRODUCT LEAKING FROM BOTTOM AREA, CAR WAS SPOTTED AT DENVER RIP TRUCKS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD SEAL PIN HANGING LOOSE BY SAFETY CHAIN, WITH VALVE CRACKED OPEN.  ALSO, BOTTOM OUTLET BLIND FLANGE HAD 3 OUT OF 4 BOTTLES LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  CLOSED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND SECURED BOTTOM OUTLET BLIND FLANGE, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  RON WOODS, CROPMATE, AND CARRY HADDOX, AGRIUM US, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY JULIE MCEE, AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD, INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED THERE WAS A 40' CONTAINER THAT WAS OBSERVED LEAKING WHILE IT WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM AN INBOUND TRAIN.  THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE SOLID, AND WAS BEING MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #16 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. AS MANAGER COOPER WAS OUT OF TOWN, HE ADVISED MS. MCGEE TO CONTACT ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES (ETS), AND HAVE THEM RESPOND WITH A TEAM TO CONTAIN AND INVESTIGATE THE LEAK.  ETS INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND AN UNKNOWN AMBER FLUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER. THE LIQUID WAS FIELD TESTED AND FOUND TO BE FLAMMABLE.  SEVERAL INCONSISTENCIES WERE NOTED AT THIS TIME.  THE RAILROAD WAYBILL INFORMATION ONLY SHOWED 1 DRUM LISTED AS A FLAMMABLE SOLID, ORGANIC , N.O.S., A STABLILZED PARA SUBSTITUTED PHENYL DIAZONIUM SALT.  THERE WAS NO INFORMATION ON ANY FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN PLACARDED WITH FLAMMABLE SOLID PLACARDS, HOWEVER, THEY WERE IMPROPERLY APPLIED, BEING PLACED SQUARE ON THE CONTAINER WITH THE LETTERING READING AT A 45 DEGREE UPWARD ANGLE FROM LEFT TO RIGHT, RATHER THAT BEING PLACED SQUARE ON POINT AS REQUIRED BY THE REGULATIONS.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS TO INSPECT THE LADING, DEVELOPED THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO SECURE THE LADING.  THERE WERE 3 EACH LARGE WOOD CRATES AT THE DOORWAY THAT MEASURED ROUGHLY 6 FOOT WIDE BY 8 FOOT LONG BY 1 FOOT HIGH WHICH WERE STACKED ON TOP OF EACH OTHER.  IT WAS APPARENT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED AS THE CRATES HAD MOVED LATERALLY WITHIN THE CONTAINER.  DIRECTLY FORWARD OF THE CRATES WERE 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS THAT HAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABELS.  THERE WAS NO LOAD SEPARATION BETWEEN THE CRATES AND THE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WERE PLACED 3 EACH TO A PALLET, WITH NO SECUREMENTS TO EACH OTHER OR TO THE PALLET.  THE DRUMS HAD BEEN LOADED WITH ADDTIONAL DRUMS PLACED ON TOP OF THE FLOOR STACKED DRUMS, AGAIN, WITH NO SEPARATION BETWEEN THE PALLET AND THE DRUMS, AND, NO SECUREMENT OF THE UPPER DRUMS.  IN ANOTHER INSTANCE PALLETS CONTAINING BAGGED GRANULATED PRODUCT, WERE PLACED ON TOP OF THE DRUMS, AGAIN, WITH NO SEPARATION BETWEEN THE PALLET AND THE DRUMS.  THE BAGGED PRODUCT WEIGHT WAS ESTIMATED TO EXCEED 1000 POUNDS. THERE IS NO RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL FOR THIS METHOD OF LOADING DRUMS, AND IT IS NOT AN APPROVED METHOD PER BOE6C FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  ETS RE-CONTACTED APL TO OBTAIN AN UPDATED BILL OF LADING, WHICH SHIPCO PROVIDED, SHOWING AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S., CONTAINING NAPTHA, WITH A WEIGHT FACTOR OF 2,724 POUNDS, WHICH WOULD REQUIRE PLACARDING FOR THE LIQUIDS.  THE INTERIOR OF THE CONTAINER WAS MONITORED FOR FLAMMABLE VAPORS, WHICH WAS BELOW THE 10% LEVEL.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, THE CONTAINER WAS VENTILATED IN THE EVENT THERE WERE OTHER UNDECLARED MATERIALS ENCOUNTERED.  AFTER REMOVING THE LARGE CRATES FROM THE REAR, INSPECTION OF T
